 market timing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Relative\, repurchase\, price(RRP)=\frac{(REP)Average\, Paid\, Repurchase\, Price}{(CP)CRSP\, ClosePrice_{\, in\,\pm t\, months}}-1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If they repurchase at low price (i.e., time market successfully), we should
 see the RRP should be negative.
 They find that in general, average (median) RRP is negative, meaning that
 managers tend to time the market.
 Around 2007-2008 (crisis), firms pay at positive RRP or repurchase at significa
nt premium (up to 8.4%).
 In years they repurchase more, the RRP is more negative (time market more).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In addition, 
\emph on
frequent repurchasers
\emph default
 pay higher prices than infrequent repurchasers.
 Frequent repurchasers are firms repurchase 
\emph on
9 or more months
\emph default
 in a given year, while infrequent repurchasers undertake 
\emph on
4 or fewer months
\emph default
 in a given years.
 Why? Infrequent repurchasers time the market, while frequent repurchasers
 have alternative motives to repurchase other than misvaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Because if they can time the market, they do so on their own account.
 RRP will be more negative in quartile with highest 
\begin_inset Formula $Net\, Insider\, Buying=(InsiderBuy-Sell)/Outstanding$
