\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, Lintner’s model implies that frms have a target payout ratio
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 measured as a fraction of their profits.
 Any difference between last period’s dividends and the target level is
 reduced by a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 each period.
 We can understand 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 as the speed of adjustment or the response of firms to transitory earning
 shocks.
 Small values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 suggest a smooth dividend policy, while a large 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 implies a more sensitivity of dividends by a large changes driven by transitory
 shocks.
\end_layout

